&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 3&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;pauldron&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to a piece of armor used to protect the shoulder. (कंधे का कवच)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The knight raised his pauldron before going into battle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In Option 3, the word &amp;quot;pauldron&amp;quot; is used as a homonym because it refers to a part of the anatomy of a sea slug rather than a piece of armor. Here, it is a metaphorical or scientific use of the word. (समुद्री जीव के कंधे जैसा हिस्सा)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The biology student dissected the pauldron of the sea slug to study its anatomy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Homonyms are words that sound or are spelled the same but have different meanings. In this case, &amp;quot;pauldron&amp;quot; has two distinct meanings: a piece of armor and a part of a sea slug&amp;#39;s anatomy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1:&lt;/strong&gt; The blacksmith polished the steel pauldron until it gleamed. (कवच को चमकाया)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The blacksmith ensured the knight&amp;#39;s pauldron was in perfect condition before the tournament.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;This refers to the literal armor piece and does not involve a homonym.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2:&lt;/strong&gt; The art historian admired the engraved pauldron of the effigy. (प्रतिमा का अलंकृत कवच)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The effigy&amp;#39;s pauldron was covered in intricate designs that reflected the era&amp;#39;s craftsmanship.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;This option also refers to the literal meaning of &amp;quot;pauldron&amp;quot; as a piece of armor.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4:&lt;/strong&gt; The museum displayed a 15th-century Italian pauldron. (15वीं सदी का कवच)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The museum&amp;#39;s pauldron was a rare artifact from the Renaissance period.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;This statement refers to an actual historic artifact, not a homonym.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;changed your habits&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;It is high time&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is followed by the past tense form of the verb.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct past tense form of the verb here is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;changed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Options 2, 3&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;4&lt;/strong&gt; are grammatically incorrect in this context.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complete Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;It is high time you &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;changed your habits&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: &amp;quot;must have changed your habits&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect as it does not fit the structure &amp;quot;It is high time&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;change your habit&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect as &amp;quot;change&amp;quot; should be in the past tense &amp;quot;changed&amp;quot;, and &amp;quot;habits&amp;quot; should be plural.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4: &amp;quot;will change the habit&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect as it does not follow the correct tense structure and does not use the appropriate noun form.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

